		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9757 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Excellent [4.68]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Ok. Maybe I'm confused, but I'm not really getting the point of quad kiting in a group. I especially don't get the concept of having someone who's *not* a druid or wizard &quot;running&quot; the quad kiting group...<br><br><blockquote><b id="fs8">dracoboars wrote:</b><hr size="1" />Also remember who is in control. You are doing all the work, if you dont like the way the group is conducting itself leave. Its much harder to find a good quad-kiter for themn then it is to find a spot in an xp group for you.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>Again. Huh!? Excuse me, but it would seem as though the quad kiters (the guys with the AOE spells) are the ones &quot;doing the work&quot;. They can quad without you. You can't quad without them.<br><br>Are you somehow defining &quot;quad kiter&quot; as someone who just grabs agro and runs around while the rest of the folks cast their AE spells? That just seems bizaare to me since it would take a pretty significant amount more time to kite the same mobs in a grup working hard to make sure not to out agro some guy who's *not* AEing, then you gain in extra exp rate. Honestly, I'd rather just quad solo with my wizard then deal with several other people in an operation that's difficult enough with just one.<br><br><br><br>[/quote]<b>I wont quad kite if any non AOE caster is in the group.</b> If the group invites a beastlord I leave immediately. You need to decide whats important to you.[/quote]<br><br>I bolded the first part because that's got to be the silliest thing I've seen posted in awhile. Um. Duh!<br><br>Not sure what you have against BLs. I agree that I don't see how they can help in a quad kite situation, but then neither do I see how rangers, or warriors, or paladins, or clerics, or any of the other classes particularly help either.<br><br><br>To the original poster. When most people talk about quad kiting, they are talking about a *single* character killing 4 mobs at once in a parallel way (ie: All at once instead of one at a time). The *only* way to do that is to use spells that damage all 4 mobs at the same time. That means targetted AE spells. Since the only two classes that get those szpells are druids and wizaards, that means that really only druids and wizards can truely AE kite. They do it exactly as posted above. You snare 4 mobs, run around them in circles until they are all on top of eachother, then drop Aes on them until they are all dead.<br><br>Any group can take on 4 mobs at a time, but in most situations, they'd be better off fighting&nbsp;&nbsp;one at a time, and in fact, they generally kill them one at a time (or split up the group againt them, which makes one wonder why they are grouped in that case). There is pretty much no real value to &quot;quadding&quot; in a group. I've seen groups single kite before (group agro kiting), and I suppose they could to 4 at a time, but why? Your melee and all non-AE casters can only hit one mob at a time when kiting, so there's no real value in adding them for quadding, and no reason to quad if you are group kiting.<br><br>There are &quot;AE groups&quot; that work, but those are generally done using PBAEs (point blank AE spells). Totally different structure for those groups. Also, they don't really involve kiting to avoid taking damage (they use chain PBAE stunning instead). If you're going to kite, you either do it solo (which may involve quadding or not), or you do it in a group (which can use quadding I suppose, but is really not very efficient IMO, since agro control becomes ridiculously difficult).</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
