		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=275512"><span id=Scholar>BatmanSixtySix</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />166 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.11]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=BatmanSixtySix&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>For the OP, Draco has a great general definition of what quad-kiting is, tho he and Gbaji are now off onto a slightly different topic. In general, in my humble experience, quading is done solo, not as a group.<br><br>My 51 druid started quadding around level 40, when he had a problem finding a good group. Well, not exactly true... When I didnt have time to stay on-line for hours trying to get into a group. I had read about quadding on Casters Realm, so I started with only pulling 2 Mobs at a time, then 3 and finally four. I am sorry to elorianBLAH, that she is not enjoying the experience. Personally, there are times when I am in a group, like last night, where I wonder why we have more down time than when I solo. Then I am thinking of the thrill of having 4 mobs try to whack on you as you rush to get your spells off, and XP for wiping them all before they get you.<br><br>While I still prefer to group, if I cant get the XP group benefits (What do you mean I dont have to do all the work?), I now go to either Dulak (Pirate Stew anyone?), the Wakening Lands or the Great Divide (Giants are fun and already slow). Personally, I start with KEI and Virtue in POK, donated for, of course. Next, I load buffs, Damage Sheilds and Wolf Form on me, cast snare on 4 DB/LB, run back and forth in either a square or triangle, wait until they all look like one MOB, and fire Lightning spells on them. I also have two 600 pt nukes loaded, in case resists leaves one of them whacking on me over his buddies corpses. The damage sheilds are important because, no matter how hard you try, you will be hit and might as well reduce the damage and hurt them back. I usually get down to 80 health, just running to snare the rest after the first one. However, unless I run right thru the middle of them, (which does happen in smaller areas), I usually keep a distance and watch THEIR health drop like a stone after that time. <br><br>This style of hunting is definitely something you have to be alert, as something like an add can go wrong at any time. (By the way, snare/root adds and have them for a snack if you still&nbsp;&nbsp;have mana and health. Otherwise, head for closest zone anouncing train coming after finishing off the others. Needless to say, I dont endorse the latter, unless worse case.) However, I usually do pretty good for plat and XP for a night, plus get items to sell on my trader kitty. <br><br><br>I hope a druid's view helps, as I see you are doing this from my cousin the ranger's side.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
